properties.name: Airport Connector
Great Allegheny Passage 2
properties.description: To Cumberland, MD

properties.name: Fort Duquesne Bridge
properties.description: Pittsburgh's first major bridge with a dedicated bike/pedestrian path. Downtown access from the bike path in Point State Park. North Shore access between Heinz Field and PNC Park on Reedsdale St, just off the North Shore Trail. Northbound, be sure to stay on the bike path and avoid the staircase.

properties.name: Roberto Clemente
properties.description: Also known as the Three Sisters Bridges. Slow and light traffic, protected bike lanes each direction. Sidewalks on both sides. Provides easy connection to the North Shore Trail from Downtown. Bridge is closed to automobiles during every Pirates home game.

properties.name: Andy Warhol
properties.description: Also known as the Three Sisters Bridges. Slow and light traffic, no shoulder. Drivers mostly respectful. Sidewalks on both sides. Provides easy connection to the North Shore Trail from Downtown.

properties.name: Rachel Carson
properties.description: Also known as the Three Sisters Bridges. Slow and light traffic, no shoulder. Drivers mostly respectful. Sidewalks on both sides. Provides easy connection to the North Shore Trail from Downtown.

properties.name: Fort Pitt Bridge
properties.description: Sidewalk on the southbound side connects Station Square (near Duquesne Incline) to Point State Park (behind Fort Pitt Museum).

properties.name: Smithfield St Bridge
properties.description: Slow moving traffic with wide shoulder and wide sidewalks on both sides. The sidewalk on the northbound side is marked mixed-use pedestrian/cyclists and provides easy access to the Station Square/South Side Trail and to the Eliza Furnace Trail nearby. Southbound, try turning into Station Square to pick up the South Side Trail and avoid E. Carson St.

properties.name: 16th St Bridge
properties.description: Medium speed traffic with no shoulder. Sidewalks on each side. Use sidewalks during rush hour as there is no room to squeeze by the traffic. Southbound takes you to the one-way Penn Ave intersection. To continue east, you must make two rights to get to Smallman St.

properties.name: Veterans Bridge
properties.description: Don't even think of biking on this one. Use sidewalk on downriver side.

properties.name: Liberty Bridge
properties.description: Use the sidewalk on the southbound side. Do not attempt to share the lane with cars. This bridge is a highway.

properties.name: S 10th St Bridge
properties.description: Slower moving traffic (heavy during rush hour), no shoulder. Wide sidewalks on both sides. Connects to the Eliza Furnace Trail on the northern side by making a right onto Second Ave.

properties.name: West Penn Railroad Bridge
properties.description: Another pleasant bicycle and pedestrian crossing that connects the North Shore Trail to Washington's Landing.

properties.name: 31st St Bridge
properties.description: Slower moving traffic with wide shoulders. Wide sidewalk on the southbound side. Connects to the North Shore Trail via River Ave.

properties.name: West End Bridge
properties.description: Fast moving traffic with no shoulder. West End Circle is confusing and dangerous. It is highly recommended to take one of the sidewalks. Northside access on Western Ave (at-grade) or via a staircase under the bridge from North Point Dr (just off the trail). Southern access from Steuben St (at-grade), or via a staircase on the West Carson St (westbound) McKees Rocks exit.

properties.name: McKees Rocks Bridge
properties.description: Fast moving traffic with no shoulders. Wide sidewalks on both sides. Pay close attention when approaching the on/off ramps.

properties.name: 40th St Bridge
properties.description: Also known as Washington's Crossing Bridge. Fast moving traffic with no shoulders, busy during rush hour. Sidewalks on both sides, with the sidewalk on the eastbound side connecting to the Millvale Riverfront Park and the Millvale Trail.

properties.name: 62nd St Bridge
properties.description: Also known as Senator Robert D. Fleming Bridge. Fast moving traffic, with good sight lines, but no shoulder. Sidewalk on the southbound side, but be careful as there is a staircase on the north end that approaches quickly.

properties.name: Highland Park Bridge
properties.description: Fast moving traffic with narrow shoulders and hectic interchanges at both ends. Sidewalk on the southbound side. Be sure to take the Freeport Rd Exit. 62nd St Bridge is a better alternative. Not recommended for the novice cyclist.

properties.name: Birmingham Bridge
properties.description: Buffered bike lanes both directions, stay VERY alert at the interchanges as cars speed on this bridge. Sidewalk on the southbound side (northern access from Forbes Ave only) with a staircase on the southern end. Oakland-bound traffic may take either Forbes Ave or the sidewalk along Fifth Ave (for a mellower ride). Take special caution on weekend nights, especially around 2AM when the bars let out.

properties.name: Hot Metal Bridge
properties.description: Pleasant bicycle and pedestrian bridge with a view. It connects the South Side Trail and SouthSide Works to the Eliza Furnace Trail and Second Ave. Recommended.

properties.name: Glenwood Bridge
properties.description: Medium to high speed traffic with no shoulder and bad sight lines. Sidewalk on both sides. The southern end of the bridge is a highway-like configuration of fast moving on/off ramps.

properties.name: Homestead Grays Bridge
properties.description: Fast moving traffic with no shoulder. Narrow sidewalks (recommended) on both sides. Take care on the approaches to the bridge and remember to yield to pedestrians.

properties.name: Rankin Bridge
properties.description: Medium speed traffic with shoulders that may accumulate debris. Sidewalk on the northbound side. Enter/exit with caution.

properties.name: Bloomfield Bridge
properties.description: Fast moving traffic, no shoulder. Sidewalk on the Oakland bound side of the bridge, but access to Bigelow Blvd (heading east to Oakland) from the sidewalk is awkward, and Bigelow Blvd (west to Downtown) is highway-like and not recommended. Use Millvale Ave to connect Bloomfield and Oakland for a better alternative. Polish Hill access via Bethoven St.

properties.name: Cemetery
properties.description: Cemetery roads are only open in the day
